      "question_text": "Too much debt (overleveraging) increases:",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "Only the company's tax deductions, which is always beneficial",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Financial risk: interest payments are fixed obligations that must be paid regardless of revenue",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Only equity returns without any downside",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Only the stock price in the short term",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "While some debt is beneficial (interest is tax-deductible and leverages equity returns), too much debt creates existential risk. Interest payments are fixed obligations regardless of revenue — if sales drop, the company still owes the same amount, potentially leading to default or bankruptcy. This is why debt-to-equity ratios and interest coverage ratios are closely watched by analysts and creditors."
    },
